From 83363b29c4d0984703035f693966c9d76b70fa2e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Fri, 26 Jun 2026 09:44:39 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] call/duct-tape: implement __pthread_canceled and
 __pthread_markcancel

The PthreadCanceled and PthreadMarkcancel RPC handlers were TODO stubs
that replied -ENOSYS for every call. That diverges from XNU, which
returns 0/EINVAL, and breaks the guest libpthread cancellation handshake:
under a cancelable-syscall + fork storm the guest spins re-issuing
dserver_callnum_pthread_canceled forever (~670/sec, 167k calls observed
while brew's portable-ruby built libunistring) -- a livelock, not a dead
hang (recv/reply stay balanced).

Carry per-thread cancellation state on the duct-tape thread (cancel_disable
/ cancel_pending / canceled, mirroring XNU's UT_CANCELDISABLE / UT_CANCEL /
UT_CANCELED uu_flag bits) and implement the two calls to XNU semantics:

  __pthread_canceled(1) -> clear cancel-disable, return 0
  __pthread_canceled(2) -> set   cancel-disable, return 0
  __pthread_canceled(0) -> if a cancel is pending and not disabled/acted,
                           mark canceled and return 0; else return EINVAL
  __pthread_markcancel(port) -> arm the target thread's pending-cancel bit

The XNU code is negated to the guest's BSD-errno convention at the call
layer (reply 0 == "canceled", -EINVAL == "not canceled").

dar-gwn.6.3
